00:05:27.700 --> 00:05:30.400
There is a phrase
that gets used a lot,

00:05:30.400 --> 00:05:32.030
and it is not even
an incorrect phrase.

00:05:32.030 --> 00:05:34.310
People talk about color contrast.

00:05:34.310 --> 00:05:38.640
And it is true, color is an aspect
of contrast as we perceive it.

00:05:38.640 --> 00:05:44.060
Different color combinations can
impact just the perceived contrast

00:05:44.060 --> 00:05:44.630
of colors.

00:05:44.630 --> 00:05:46.260
Some things are more legible.

00:05:46.260 --> 00:05:49.910
Invert them, and maybe one or the
other is going to be more legible

00:05:49.910 --> 00:05:50.680
for you.

00:05:50.680 --> 00:05:53.880
However, the reality
is in these guidelines,

00:05:53.880 --> 00:05:55.950
in the Web Content
Accessibility Guidelines,

00:05:57.580 --> 00:06:02.570
they actually do not talk
about color contrast.

00:06:02.570 --> 00:06:06.030
What they talk about in
WCAG is luminance contrast.

00:06:06.030 --> 00:06:08.310
And what that means is it's not
about the colors you choose;

00:06:08.310 --> 00:06:13.190
it's about the brightness
difference between these colors.

00:06:13.190 --> 00:06:15.260
The full term that's
used in these guidelines

00:06:15.260 --> 00:06:17.320
is Relative Luminance Contrast.

00:06:17.320 --> 00:06:18.360
So what does that mean?

00:06:18.360 --> 00:06:20.950
What it means is,
the way our screens work,

00:06:20.950 --> 00:06:23.540
we’re really seeing three colors.

00:06:23.540 --> 00:06:27.030
You got black, and then you got
three colors that are presented red,

00:06:27.030 --> 00:06:28.510
green, and blue.

00:06:28.510 --> 00:06:30.139
And pure red is pretty hard to read

00:06:30.140 --> 00:06:32.000
when it is used on
a white background.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:34.460
Pure green is also
pretty hard to read.

00:06:34.460 --> 00:06:37.280
Maybe even brighter and
harder to read than the blue.

00:06:37.280 --> 00:06:39.060
I have actually added
a little outline.

00:06:39.060 --> 00:06:42.430
It's just, I am trying to
make my inaccessible visuals

00:06:42.430 --> 00:06:46.900
a bit more accessible with a few
little techniques here and there.

00:06:46.900 --> 00:06:50.710
But that red and green is
just kind of hard to see.

00:06:50.710 --> 00:06:53.823
And so what is found
within these guidelines

00:06:53.824 --> 00:06:57.630
is a fairly complex formula to try
to weigh these different colors.

00:06:57.630 --> 00:06:59.560
Don’t worry about the formula;
it's just a slide to say,

00:06:59.560 --> 00:07:03.040
Look at all this math is
pretty much what's going on.

00:07:03.040 --> 00:07:05.520
But what it does is it
weighs the red and the green

00:07:05.520 --> 00:07:08.970
and the blue that are used and just
kind of looks at the brightness

00:07:08.970 --> 00:07:12.710
of those, and creates a
ratio between two colors.

00:07:12.710 --> 00:07:18.060
Now, the highest this ratio can be is
21-to-1, and that's black and white.

00:07:18.060 --> 00:07:20.570
It does not matter if it's black
on white or white on black,

00:07:20.570 --> 00:07:26.220
it's that same ratio, and that's
the case with all of this.

00:07:26.220 --> 00:07:29.070
If you swap those colors,
the ratio is still the same.

00:07:30.210 --> 00:07:35.650
Now, this is a lot of contrast,
and the highest isn't always best.

00:07:35.650 --> 00:07:38.060
A lot of black and white
can be kind of jarring.

00:07:39.240 --> 00:07:43.390
So what is within WCAG within
these guidelines is a minimum level

00:07:43.390 --> 00:07:44.390
of contrast.

00:07:45.270 --> 00:07:48.580
And it's 4.5 to one
according to that formula.

00:07:48.580 --> 00:07:51.520
