to non-text contrast later
on, but that’s three.

00:13:36.740 --> 00:13:44.110
I am going to just jump
onto this use of color,

00:13:44.110 --> 00:13:46.600
which is going to give me
my fourth check right now.

00:13:46.600 --> 00:13:50.330
So another requirement,
and the number for this is 1.4.1.

00:13:50.330 --> 00:13:53.160
And for keeping track,
it is level single A,

00:13:53.160 --> 00:13:56.000
but this requirement
is called use of color.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:59.580
Now there's two important
things related to this.

00:13:59.580 --> 00:14:01.730
A lot of times what it comes to
mind when people talk about use

00:14:01.730 --> 00:14:05.640
of color is do not rely on color
like red and green for pass

00:14:05.640 --> 00:14:07.200
and fail and things like that.

00:14:07.200 --> 00:14:10.460
That's true, and we’re
going to come back to that.

00:14:10.460 --> 00:14:15.980
However, there is another important
way that color can be used.

00:14:15.980 --> 00:14:20.540
Sometimes it's requiring that someone
can distinguish a certain color.

00:14:20.540 --> 00:14:21.840
I can see red.

00:14:21.840 --> 00:14:23.260
I can see green.

00:14:23.260 --> 00:14:27.130
But sometimes color is used
to distinguish an element

00:14:27.130 --> 00:14:30.160
to differentiate it
from something else.

00:14:30.160 --> 00:14:32.960
And it's not so much the
color you’re are using;

00:14:32.960 --> 00:14:37.040
it’s the difference between colors
that's giving you information.

00:14:37.040 --> 00:14:38.930
A common example of this is a link.

00:14:40.140 --> 00:14:41.970
We have this link here
in the screenshot.

00:14:41.970 --> 00:14:45.690
And I have tried to add some
borders and a few things just to...

00:14:45.690 --> 00:14:50.760
I do not want my own slides
to have accessibility issues.

00:14:50.760 --> 00:14:53.120
I do not want to rely on
color in my own slides,

00:14:53.120 --> 00:14:55.970
so I tried to put an
order around this.

00:14:55.970 --> 00:15:01.770
But this terms of use,
because it's not underlined,

00:15:01.770 --> 00:15:05.220
because it's just a color difference,
that's being used to tell me

00:15:05.220 --> 00:15:06.230
that's a link.

00:15:06.230 --> 00:15:07.750
This would fail that requirement.

00:15:07.750 --> 00:15:09.780
One of the things it says
that you cannot do using

00:15:09.780 --> 00:15:11.900
just color is you
can not rely on color

00:15:11.900 --> 00:15:14.460
for distinguishing
a visual element.

00:15:14.460 --> 00:15:17.860
In other words, this isn't
body text; this is a link,

00:15:17.860 --> 00:15:19.850
and you can not rely on just
a color difference for that.

00:15:21.340 --> 00:15:24.770
I'm going to talk about that
requirement a little bit more,

00:15:24.770 --> 00:15:28.100
just focusing in on the
difference between this link text

00:15:28.100 --> 00:15:29.140
and the label text here.

00:15:30.370 --> 00:15:34.140
By the way,
these colors that I am going to use,

00:15:34.140 --> 00:15:37.110
these are colors that are
pulled exactly from, like,

00:15:37.110 --> 00:15:39.880
a Fortune 100 Company
that we worked with,

00:15:39.880 --> 00:15:42.120
and these are the colors they
were using for their links.

00:15:42.120 --> 00:15:47.020
This is the process we went through
talking about this with them.

00:15:47.020 --> 00:15:49.240
First of all,
you might think, Oh, no,

00:15:49.240 --> 00:15:51.080
those colors are pretty different.

00:15:51.080 --> 00:15:54.170
They are actually not.

00:15:54.170 --> 00:15:57.030
OK, the colors are different,
but the brightness difference

00:15:57.030 --> 00:16:00.050
between the two is
actually not a lot.

00:16:00.050 --> 00:16:03.900
The contrast difference,
they are almost the same.

00:16:03.900 --> 00:16:07.570
Some people do have difficulty
distinguishing gray and blue text.

00:16:07.570 --> 00:16:10.350
I've talked to a couple
people who told me that

00:16:10.350 --> 00:16:12.210
and shared that experience.

00:16:12.210 --> 00:16:16.340
And so if someone has difficulty
distinguishing gray and blue,

00:16:16.340 --> 00:16:21.740
this is a slide trying to
simulate what that might be like

00:16:21.740 --> 00:16:22.420
for that person.

00:16:22.420 --> 00:16:26.260
In terms of use, while very
slightly different, it's really hard

00:16:26.260 --> 00:16:27.260
to distinguish that.

00:16:28.260 --> 00:16:31.610
In fact, if you were just
reading through lines of text,

00:16:31.610 --> 00:16:34.740
even if you have good contrast
sensitivity, I think you're going

00:16:34.740 --> 00:16:36.170
to have a hard time
picking up the links.

00:16:37.460 --> 00:16:42.850
So that is just giving
you an idea of that issue.

00:16:42.850 --> 00:16:45.850
Now, when we were working
with this client, they said,

00:16:45.850 --> 00:16:47.410
Well, what if I just bold this?

00:16:47.410 --> 00:16:50.110
What if I use bold to
distinguish this link?

00:16:50.110 --> 00:16:51.800
And so let's see if I
were to pull out the color

00:16:51.800 --> 00:16:54.530
and just look at the
contrast difference there.

00:16:54.530 --> 00:16:57.870
That definitely does work.

00:16:57.870 --> 00:17:01.190
You now have distinguished your
links using more than just color.

00:17:02.450 --> 00:17:09.510
However, that only works if you only
use bold just for identifying links,

00:17:09.510 --> 00:17:11.170
and that's almost never the case.

00:17:11.170 --> 00:17:13.290
With this client, and a lot of
other people who we worked with

00:17:13.290 --> 00:17:17.470
on this issue, at some point
they use bold to emphasize text.

00:17:17.470 --> 00:17:20.680
So you might say, Well, I have read
and agreed to the terms of use,

00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:24.690
or, You must do this. Or it's
just, anywhere in that nearby text,

00:17:24.690 --> 00:17:27.380
you bold something to emphasize
it, well, now you are back

00:17:27.380 --> 00:17:31.550
to relying on color, and now you are
back to failing this requirement.

00:17:31.550 --> 00:17:39.550
So that’s a workaround that just
doesn't work most of the time.

00:17:41.450 --> 00:17:44.150
There’s a question that I know
has just popped up in Q&A.

00:17:44.150 --> 00:17:47.320
So does this meet this
criteria of colors used?

00:17:47.320 --> 00:17:50.400
And the link is underlined
when hovering a mouse over it.

00:17:50.400 --> 00:17:52.120
So I’m going to come to that.

00:17:52.120 --> 00:17:56.820
Before I do it, I just want to
say, let's underline our links.

00:17:56.820 --> 00:17:59.090
I think that's going
to be best practice.

00:17:59.090 --> 00:18:01.920
Not all links, not all the time,
but where they're appearing next

00:18:01.920 --> 00:18:04.800
to other non-linked
text, body text.

00:18:04.800 --> 00:18:08.570
It just make them better,
it makes them, I think, more usable,

00:18:08.570 --> 00:18:11.680
more mobile-friendly,
more scannable,

00:18:11.680 --> 00:18:15.410
easier to track a link across
line breaks, and things like that.

00:18:15.410 --> 00:18:17.570
So there's just a lot of good
reasons to underline your links.

00:18:18.960 --> 00:18:19.850
So what's required?

00:18:19.850 --> 00:18:23.990
And this actually, I think, goes to
the question that Beatrice asked,

00:18:23.990 --> 00:18:28.890
and that is, you've got not
just the contrast requirement,

00:18:28.890 --> 00:18:32.730
but what if the link is underlined
when hovering the mouse over it?

00:18:32.730 --> 00:18:36.800
So that on its own does
not meet this requirement,

00:18:36.800 --> 00:18:40.020
but it is a part of
meeting this requirement.

00:18:40.020 --> 00:18:46.160
So if you aren't underlining those
links, there are two requirements.

00:18:46.160 --> 00:18:50.810
One is that there is a 3-to-1
contrast ratio between the link text

00:18:50.810 --> 00:18:53.170
and the non-link text.

00:18:53.170 --> 00:18:56.250
The idea with this is, if you give
it enough of a contrast difference,

00:18:56.250 --> 00:19:00.270
now you're not relying on someone
being able to differentiate colors;

00:19:00.270 --> 00:19:03.430
you are allowing them to just
differentiate the contrast,

00:19:03.430 --> 00:19:05.640
and just tell the difference
between, Well, this text is lighter

00:19:05.640 --> 00:19:08.420
or darker than this other text.

00:19:08.420 --> 00:19:11.800
And we’re are going to use a
tool in just a minute to show

00:19:11.800 --> 00:19:12.800
how you can do that.

00:19:13.790 --> 00:19:17.380
The second part to this,
though, is kind of related

00:19:17.380 --> 00:19:18.400
to what was just asked.

00:19:18.400 --> 00:19:21.820
The link must present a
change, a non-colored queue.

00:19:21.820 --> 00:19:23.870
So more than just a color change.

00:19:23.870 --> 00:19:25.880
And that typically
means bringing back

00:19:25.880 --> 00:19:29.380
that underline on keyboard focus.

00:19:29.380 --> 00:19:33.620
It actually isn't required for
mouse hover, because the idea

00:19:33.620 --> 00:19:35.650
with mouse hovers, is you're
already hovering with your mouse,

00:19:35.650 --> 00:19:37.930
and you already have
a pointer there.

00:19:37.930 --> 00:19:41.450
If it's a link... And this is,
by the way, just for links.

00:19:41.450 --> 00:19:43.410
It's not for buttons
or other things.

00:19:43.410 --> 00:19:46.430
This requirement, it just
specifically calls out links.

00:19:46.430 --> 00:19:53.250
It's kind of weird, but it does...
When you hover over link,

00:19:53.250 --> 00:19:54.620
you also get that cursor change.

00:19:54.620 --> 00:19:56.390
It changes to that finger.

00:19:56.390 --> 00:19:59.900
And so technically it's not required,
but it's a really, really good idea.

00:19:59.900 --> 00:20:03.180
If you are going to bring back
that underline, bring it back

00:20:03.180 --> 00:20:04.180
for the hover as well.

00:20:05.370 --> 00:20:08.160
So let's use this contrast checker.

00:20:08.160 --> 00:20:12.020
I'm going to go back to this page.

00:20:12.020 --> 00:20:13.870
Let me refresh this page.

00:20:13.870 --> 00:20:15.630
I'm actually going to
make it a bit larger.

00:20:15.630 --> 00:20:19.450
So we do have a link here,
kind of moving down this list.

00:20:19.450 --> 00:20:22.520
This I've read and agreed to...
And this time, it says copyright

00:20:22.520 --> 00:20:23.520
in terms of use.

00:20:24.760 --> 00:20:28.890
So these are the same colors
as was used in that slide.

00:20:28.890 --> 00:20:32.870
Now, if I want to test this,
I can use a link-contrast checker.

00:20:35.200 --> 00:20:42.490
This link contrast checker, what
it does is it adds another option.

00:20:42.490 --> 00:20:45.570
When I was using WAVE,
I had these two options for color.

00:20:45.570 --> 00:20:49.120
I had a slider for the text color
and a slider for the background,

00:20:49.120 --> 00:20:51.780
or options for the text
color and background color.

00:20:51.780 --> 00:20:56.270
This one has two different text
options: link and body text.

00:20:56.270 --> 00:21:01.220
So with link and body text,
I've pre-populated this

00:21:01.220 --> 00:21:03.170
with the two colors
that I've been using.

00:21:03.170 --> 00:21:07.440
So it's a blue that does
have at least 4.5 to one.

00:21:07.440 --> 00:21:09.930
You've got the body text that
also has at least 4.5 to one.

00:21:09.930 --> 00:21:12.726
So the link and body text pass

00:21:12.727 --> 00:21:16.920
on their own the text
contrast requirement.

00:21:18.160 --> 00:21:21.720
However, as I mentioned, they
have almost no contrast difference

00:21:21.720 --> 00:21:22.660
between them.

00:21:22.660 --> 00:21:25.150
So if I don't want to underline
my links, I am going to have

00:21:25.150 --> 00:21:26.690
to use a different color.

00:21:26.690 --> 00:21:32.100
Now I can not really go lighter
because if I go lighter very quickly,

00:21:32.100 --> 00:21:35.820
before I meet that three to
one difference between link

00:21:35.820 --> 00:21:41.380
and body text, very quickly,
I will get too low of contrast text.

00:21:41.380 --> 00:21:44.120
So in order to have 3-to-1
difference between the blue and gray,

00:21:44.120 --> 00:21:48.720
I have got to get that so light that
it only has 1.5 to one contrast.

00:21:53.980 --> 00:21:56.670
So the way I did that using this
link contrast checker, by the way,

00:21:56.670 --> 00:22:01.320
and other contrast checkers is
that there is a lightness slider,

00:22:01.320 --> 00:22:04.540
and that just tries to change
the lightness and darkness

00:22:04.540 --> 00:22:07.530
of that same keyword color.

00:22:07.530 --> 00:22:08.530
So that's not going to work.

00:22:09.410 --> 00:22:11.590
Neither is going
lighter with the gray.

00:22:11.590 --> 00:22:14.030
What you need to do is go
darker with one of those colors.

00:22:14.030 --> 00:22:17.300
I think it probably makes the most
sense to go darker with that gray.

00:22:17.300 --> 00:22:20.130
Otherwise, it basically looks like
you've got black links, you know,

00:22:20.130 --> 00:22:22.090
by the time it's dark enough.

00:22:22.090 --> 00:22:26.800
So dark gray text with that
same color blue for the links,

00:22:26.800 --> 00:22:29.210
this would now meet
that requirement.

00:22:30.360 --> 00:22:32.210
And that's something that I can do.

