00:40:58.640 --> 00:41:00.630
I'm actually going to
walk you back here.

00:41:00.630 --> 00:41:02.790
And I'm just going
to leave it at 16.

00:41:02.790 --> 00:41:05.830
But you actually would need to
test all the other possible states

00:41:05.830 --> 00:41:07.320
of this button as well.

00:41:07.320 --> 00:41:09.780
So it's actually going to be
16-plus, closer to 20.

00:41:11.020 --> 00:41:13.110
So let's say I submit this
thing and I've got an error.

00:41:14.120 --> 00:41:22.110
And so now with this error,
I've got a checkbox that's now red.

00:41:22.110 --> 00:41:24.340
So a couple of things
with this red checkbox.

00:41:24.340 --> 00:41:27.490
One is that I now need to test
the contrast of this thing.

00:41:27.490 --> 00:41:30.240
So does it have at least 3-to-1
contrast at the background

00:41:30.240 --> 00:41:31.890
in its error state?

00:41:31.890 --> 00:41:35.800
I've introduced an additional state
now that this thing has an error.

00:41:37.260 --> 00:41:39.010
So that's 17.

00:41:40.780 --> 00:41:44.510
Then what about the difference
between the error state

00:41:44.510 --> 00:41:46.230
and the focus state?

00:41:46.230 --> 00:41:50.310
So before saying, OK, we got that
black or really dark checkbox,

00:41:50.310 --> 00:41:52.470
got this bright blue
focus indicator.

00:41:52.470 --> 00:41:56.510
I'm good to go, right?
Well, what if there's an error?

00:41:56.510 --> 00:42:01.970
The difference you're looking
for is between the unfocused

00:42:01.970 --> 00:42:04.060
and the focused
state of that thing.

00:42:04.060 --> 00:42:07.750
And when it's got an error,
the unfocused state is now red.

00:42:07.750 --> 00:42:11.000
And so I failed again, unless I
would have added maybe that...

00:42:11.000 --> 00:42:14.280
That’s another reason,
another plug for adding that outline.

00:42:15.550 --> 00:42:18.130
So that's that one.

00:42:18.130 --> 00:42:20.154
Probably the big one
here is you've got color

00:42:20.155 --> 00:42:21.430
that's prompting a response.

00:42:22.470 --> 00:42:26.450
So with this color prompting a
response, that's going to be a use

00:42:26.450 --> 00:42:27.730
of color failure.

00:42:27.730 --> 00:42:29.260
And you might say, Well,
wait, I thought I had

00:42:29.260 --> 00:42:33.660
at least 3-to-1 contrast like the
link text. Well, this is different.

00:42:33.660 --> 00:42:36.240
The reason this is different is
because you're not just saying,

00:42:36.240 --> 00:42:37.670
here's a color difference.

00:42:37.670 --> 00:42:42.020
You're actually using the
color red to convey meaning.

00:42:42.020 --> 00:42:46.220
This requires that I can detect
and differentiate the color red

00:42:46.220 --> 00:42:48.430
from all other colors.

00:42:48.430 --> 00:42:50.561
And so even if this
has enough contrast,

00:42:50.562 --> 00:42:52.120
this would still be a failure

00:42:52.120 --> 00:42:58.290
of that use of color requirement
because I got to be able to see red

00:42:58.290 --> 00:42:59.490
and tell it apart from others.

00:43:00.970 --> 00:43:01.790
So what would I want to do?

00:43:01.790 --> 00:43:05.810
Maybe I'd want to add an icon
and some kind of an alert

00:43:05.810 --> 00:43:09.840
in addition to that color to let
me know that there's an error,

00:43:09.840 --> 00:43:10.840
and that's great.

00:43:11.790 --> 00:43:16.870
Now, this would be something that I'd
also need to test the contrast of.

00:43:16.870 --> 00:43:19.370
So one little aside
here with this contrast,

00:43:20.400 --> 00:43:26.080
and that is I've used a white
background for all of these slides.

00:43:26.080 --> 00:43:29.720
Often, I'll see a form, for example,
or maybe even like this bottom part

00:43:29.720 --> 00:43:31.190
of the form where it's
like a lighter gray.

00:43:32.430 --> 00:43:36.500
When it comes to testing
contrast of shapes,

00:43:36.500 --> 00:43:39.830
it's not always just two colors.

00:43:39.830 --> 00:43:43.880
The term that's used in WCAG to
describe the contrast requirements is

00:43:43.880 --> 00:43:46.640
that it's against adjacent colors.

00:43:46.640 --> 00:43:50.150
The parts of the shape
that I need to perceive

00:43:50.150 --> 00:43:51.780
in order to know what's going on.

00:43:51.780 --> 00:43:55.850
And for an alert icon specifically,
a triangle is part of that shape.

00:43:55.850 --> 00:43:59.960
Now, if it were a circle or a square
or just an exclamation mark, fine.

00:43:59.960 --> 00:44:03.250
But because I've decided to use
a triangle, and that is a symbol

00:44:03.250 --> 00:44:09.380
for an alert, now I’d have to
test really the white contrast

00:44:09.380 --> 00:44:10.860
from the red.

00:44:10.860 --> 00:44:15.080
And if that has at least 3-to-1, I'm
good, which, in this case, it does.

00:44:15.080 --> 00:44:18.690
But the red against the
gray background does not.

00:44:18.690 --> 00:44:22.420
It has less than 3-to-1, and so
that this would actually fail that

00:44:22.420 --> 00:44:27.410
because this triangle, I need to
perceive or distinguish the triangle

00:44:27.410 --> 00:44:28.410
from the background.

00:44:29.210 --> 00:44:31.890
One I can address this is
to add order to the icons.

00:44:31.890 --> 00:44:35.080
If you do that in general, to the
little icons you're using like that,

00:44:35.080 --> 00:44:37.700
then you can be confident that
it will have enough contrast

00:44:37.700 --> 00:44:38.980
on any color background.

00:44:40.220 --> 00:44:41.290
OK, so we are real close.

00:44:41.290 --> 00:44:42.650
We are almost done here.

00:44:42.650 --> 00:44:44.850
Just going to wrap it
up with one final thing,

00:44:44.850 --> 00:44:46.580
and that is an error message.

00:44:46.580 --> 00:44:48.780
So what if I add an error message?

00:44:48.780 --> 00:44:50.850
You must agree to the
terms of use to continue.

00:44:52.490 --> 00:44:58.040
So one final thing related
to graphics is that you need

00:44:58.040 --> 00:45:01.710
to have that 3-to-1 contrast
if the graphic is required

00:45:01.710 --> 00:45:06.360
to understand what's going
on, if it's an enhancement.

00:45:07.560 --> 00:45:09.570
And in this case,
it's become an enhancement.

00:45:09.570 --> 00:45:11.830
There's no contrast requirement.

00:45:11.830 --> 00:45:14.530
Now it's great that it's there and
I would definitely recommend it,

00:45:14.530 --> 00:45:17.540
but the error message on its
own is enough to tell you

00:45:17.540 --> 00:45:19.950
that there's an error here.

00:45:19.950 --> 00:45:20.680
It appeared.

00:45:20.680 --> 00:45:22.170
It wasn't there before.

00:45:22.170 --> 00:45:24.150
You must agree to the
terms of use to continue,

00:45:24.150 --> 00:45:30.520
it tells me that this
is an in an error state.

00:45:30.520 --> 00:45:34.330
So in that case, I would need to
test the contrast, the error message.

00:45:34.330 --> 00:45:39.110
I would still highly recommend
a good high contrast alert icon,

00:45:39.110 --> 00:45:45.110
but on its own,
that would not be required.

00:45:46.140 --> 00:45:48.860
So we made it.

00:45:48.860 --> 00:45:50.270
I know that was that
was pretty quick.

00:45:50.270 --> 00:45:53.210
That was about as fast as
I know how to go with this.

00:45:53.210 --> 00:45:55.240
But that just gives you an idea
that we're actually up to 20,

00:45:55.240 --> 00:45:58.120
and really even more with
that button that I threw in;

00:45:58.120 --> 00:46:00.480
different things that
you would need to test.

00:46:00.480 --> 00:46:03.660
So just be mindful with
your contrast testing.

00:46:03.660 --> 00:46:06.980
I think the big key is
interact with that thing.

00:46:06.980 --> 00:46:10.340
You interact, figure out what
are its different states.

00:46:10.340 --> 00:46:13.670
Submit things with errors so
that you can test the errors

00:46:13.670 --> 00:46:15.030
of those as well.

00:46:15.030 --> 00:46:16.830
And I think those are
going to be the real keys

00:46:16.830 --> 00:46:21.510
to really bring the number of
those checks up pretty quickly.

