00:47:10.070 --> 00:47:11.810
And it's very often not white.

00:47:11.810 --> 00:47:13.400
It's going to be some other color.

00:47:13.400 --> 00:47:19.420
So yes.

00:47:19.420 --> 00:47:22.220
Gary asked that question about
not relying fully on color

00:47:22.220 --> 00:47:24.970
of contrast,
and also using ARIA attributes.

00:47:24.970 --> 00:47:28.870
I think a key to the question
that you asked, Jerry or Gary,

00:47:28.870 --> 00:47:34.700
is definitely also ARIA attributes.

00:47:34.700 --> 00:47:36.550
This is everything.

00:47:36.550 --> 00:47:41.100
All we've talked about 100% has
been about the visual experience,

00:47:41.100 --> 00:47:44.460
and you would definitely want to
enhance that experience using ARIA

00:47:44.460 --> 00:47:47.170
to make sure that somebody knows,
for example, it's in an error state,

00:47:47.170 --> 00:47:49.340
and has that error message read.

00:47:49.340 --> 00:47:51.500
But that would be in addition
to all of those color

00:47:51.500 --> 00:47:55.560
and contrast requirements still
being in place regardless of the ARIA

00:47:55.560 --> 00:47:59.200
that you are using.

00:48:02.120 --> 00:48:04.000
Avoiding placement of text
on gradient backgrounds

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:05.760
is generally best practice? Yes.

00:48:05.760 --> 00:48:06.330
I think so.

00:48:06.330 --> 00:48:08.150
Or busy images.

00:48:08.150 --> 00:48:10.990
I mean, sometimes a gradient
can be quite subtle,

00:48:10.990 --> 00:48:15.200
and I think that's OK, but a
really pretty significant gradient

00:48:15.200 --> 00:48:19.850
or very busy background images.

00:48:19.850 --> 00:48:21.840
Would you say that avoiding
the placement of text

00:48:21.840 --> 00:48:24.450
on a gradient background
is generally best practice?

00:48:24.450 --> 00:48:27.200
I think in general, unless
that gradient is pretty subtle.

